{{Infobox scientist |name = Joe Klemp |image = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')--> |image_size = |alt = |caption = |birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |birth_place = |death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> |death_place = |fields = [[Chemical engineering]], [[atmospheric sciences]] |workplaces = [[National Center for Atmospheric Research]] |alma_mater = [[Stanford University]] <small>(Ph.D., 1971)</small> |thesis_title = Extensions of Laminar Boundary Layer Theory to Flows with Separation |thesis_url = |thesis_year = 1971 |doctoral_advisor = [[Andreas Acrivos]] |known_for = [[Computer simulation|Numerical simulations]] illuminating [[atmospheric dynamics]] |influences = [[Robert B. Wilhelmson]], [[Richard Rotunno]], [[Douglas K. Lilly]], [[Morris Weisman]] |influenced = [[Paul Markowski]] |awards = [[Carl-Gustaf Rossby Research Medal]] }}
'''Joseph Bernard Klemp''' is an American [[atmospheric scientist]] who collaborated in groundbreaking work advancing [[Computer simulation|numerical simulation]] techniques and uncovering the [[Atmospheric dynamics|dynamics]] of [[atmospheric convection]], including [[supercell]] thunderstorms, [[tornado]]es,<ref>{{cite web |title = What Makes a Tornado? |work = UCAR at 50: The 50th anniversary report of UCAR and NCAR |publisher = National Center for Atmospheric Research |date = Sep 2010 |url = http://www2.ucar.edu/ucarat50/what-makes-a-tornado |accessdate = 2014-03-20 |archiveurl = |archivedate = }}</ref> [[squall line]]s, as well as [[mountain wave]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title = NCAR Scientist to Receive Rossby Research Medal and AMS Service Award |work = The Front Page |publisher = [[American Meteorological Society]] |date = 26 Jan 2011 |url = http://blog.ametsoc.org/uncategorized/ncar-scientist-to-receive-rossby-research-medal-and-ams-service-award/ |accessdate = 2014-03-20 |archiveurl = |archivedate = }}</ref>
