The [[Bayer designation]] '''Nu Columbae''' (ν Col / ν Columbae) is shared by two [[star]]s, in the [[constellation]] [[Columba]]: *[[Nu¹ Columbae|ν¹ Columbae]] *[[Nu² Columbae|ν² Columbae]]
{{SIA |astronomical objects}}
[[Category:Bayer objects|Columbae, Nu]] [[Category:Columba (constellation)]]

{{Jurassic}} The '''Pliensbachian''' is an [[age (geology)|age]] of the [[geologic timescale]] and [[stage (stratigraphy)|stage]] in the stratigraphic column. It is part of the [[Early Jurassic|Early or Lower Jurassic]] [[epoch (geology)|epoch]] or [[series (stratigraphy)|series]] and spans the time between 190.8 ± 1.5 [[annum|Ma]] and 182.7 ± 1.5 Ma (million years ago).<ref name="benton, 2012">{{cite book|last=Benton|first=Michael J.|title=Prehistoric Life|year=2012|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|location=Edinburgh, Scotland|isbn=978-0-7566-9910-9|pages=44–45}}</ref> The Pliensbachian is preceded by the [[Sinemurian]] and followed by the [[Toarcian]].<ref>See Gradstein ''et al.'' (2004) for a detailed geologic timescale</ref>
[[File:Drzewica Formation Reconstruction.jpg|right|thumb|Example of a Pliensbachian ecosystem, the [[Drzewica Formation]] of [[Szydłowiec]] in [[Poland]], characterised by a very damp ecosystem, populated by dinosaur megafauna]] The Pliensbachian ended with the [[extinction event]] called the [[Toarcian turnover]]. During the Pliensbachian, the middle part of the [[Lias Group|Lias]] was deposited in Europe. The Pliensbachian is roughly coeval with the [[Charmouthian]] regional stage of [[North America]].
==Stratigraphic definitions== The Pliensbachian takes its name from the hamlet of [[Pliensbach]] in the community of [[Zell unter Aichelberg]] in the [[Swabian Alb]], some 30&nbsp;km east of [[Stuttgart]] in [[Germany]]. The name was introduced into scientific literature by German palaeontologist [[Albert Oppel]] in 1858.
The base of the Pliensbachian is at the first appearances of the ammonite species ''[[Bifericeras|Bifericeras donovani]]'' and [[genus|genera]] ''[[Apoderoceras]]'' and ''[[Gleviceras]]''. The Wine Haven profile near [[Robin Hood's Bay]] ([[Yorkshire]], [[England]]) has been appointed as global reference profile for the base ([[GSSP]]).<ref>Meister ''et al.'' (2006)</ref>
The top of the Pliensbachian (the base of the Toarcian stage) is at the first appearance of ammonite genus ''[[Eodactylites]]''.
===Biostratigraphy=== [[File:Pleuroceras spinatum MHNT.PAL.CEP.2001.86.jpg|right|thumb|''Pleuroceras spinatum'' [[:fr:Muséum de Toulouse|Museum of Toulouse]]]] The Pliensbachian contains five ammonite [[biozone]]s in the [[boreal domain]]: *zone of ''[[Pleuroceras spinatum]]'' *zone of ''[[Amaltheus|Amaltheus margaritatus]]'' *zone of ''[[Prodactylioceras|Prodactylioceras davoei]]'' *zone of ''[[Tragophylloceras|Tragophylloceras ibex]]'' *zone of ''[[Uptonia|Uptonia jamesoni]]''
In the [[Tethys Ocean|Tethys domain]], the Pliensbachian contains six biozones: *zone of ''[[Emaciaticeras|Emaciaticeras emaciatum]]'' *zone of ''[[Arieticeras|Arieticeras algovianum]]'' *zone of ''[[Fuciniceras|Fuciniceras lavinianum]]'' *zone of ''Prodactylioceras davoei'' *zone of ''Tragophylloceras ibex'' *zone of ''Uptonia jamesoni''
==Palaeontology==
