The '''Schumann–Runge bands''' are a set of [[absorption band]]s of [[molecular oxygen]] that occur at wavelengths between 176 and 192.6 nanometres.<ref name="BrasseurSolomon2006">{{cite book|author1=Guy P. Brasseur|author2=Susan Solomon|title=Aeronomy of the Middle Atmosphere: Chemistry and Physics of the Stratosphere and Mesosphere|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z5OtlDjfXkkC&pg=PA223|date=15 January 2006|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4020-3824-2|pages=223–}}</ref><ref name="Salby2012">{{cite book|author=Murry L. Salby|title=Physics of the Atmosphere and Climate|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CeMdwj7J48QC&pg=PA222|date=16 January 2012|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0-521-76718-7|pages=222–}}</ref> The bands are named for [[Victor Schumann]] and [[Carl David Tolmé Runge|Carl Runge]].

